'''Douglas Wayne Sahm''' (November 6, 1941 – November 18, 1999) was an American musician, singer-songwriter and [[multi-instrumentalist]] born in [[San Antonio, Texas]]. Sahm is regarded as one of the main figures of [[Tejano music|Tex-Mex music]], and as an important performer of [[Music of Texas|Texan Music]]. He gained fame along with his band, the [[Sir Douglas Quintet]], with a top-twenty hit in the United States and the United Kingdom with "[[She's About a Mover]]" (1965). Sahm was influenced by the San Antonio music scene that included [[conjunto]] and [[blues]], and later by the [[hippie]] scene of [[San Francisco]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Garcia |first=Camille |date=November 15, 2016 |title=Sir Doug Tells Lesser-known Story of SA's Doug Sahm, the 'Groover's Groover' |url=http://sanantonioreport.org/sir-doug-tells-lesser-known-story-of-sas-doug-sahm-the-groovers-groover/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230321210522/https://sanantonioreport.org/sir-doug-tells-lesser-known-story-of-sas-doug-sahm-the-groovers-groover/ |archive-date=March 21, 2023 |access-date=May 23, 2024 |website=San Antonio Report |language=en-US}}</ref> With his blend of music, he found success performing in [[Austin, Texas]], as the hippie counterculture soared in the 1970s.

Sahm began singing at age five and learned to play the steel guitar at age six. He was considered a [[child prodigy]] on the instrument. By the age of eight, he had appeared on the ''[[Louisiana Hayride]]''. He made his recording debut as "Little Doug" in 1955, and was influenced by [[rock and roll]] during his teenage years. Sahm had local hit records, while he played clubs as a musician for other bands. In 1965, [[Huey P. Meaux]] produced Sahm and the Sir Douglas Quintet's "She's About a Mover". The same year, Sahm moved to California. In 1971, he returned to San Antonio, and soon after he moved to Austin. [[Atlantic Records]] signed Sahm and released his debut solo album ''[[Doug Sahm and Band]]'' in 1973.

After a continuing decline in record sales, Sahm kept performing in clubs in Austin, and moved through different record labels. Meanwhile, he enjoyed success in Sweden and in Canada. In 1989, Sahm formed the [[Supergroup (music)|supergroup]] the [[Texas Tornados]] with fellow Tex-Mex musicians [[Augie Meyers]], [[Freddy Fender]] and [[Flaco Jiménez]]. The Texas Tornados toured successfully, and one of their releases earned a [[Grammy Award]]. In 1999, Sahm died during a vacation trip. A posthumous album, ''[[The Return of Wayne Douglas]]'', was released in 2000. Sahm received multiple honors in the state of Texas, including hall of fame inductions and memorials in public places.

==Early life and start in music==
Doug Sahm was born in [[San Antonio, Texas]], on November&nbsp;6, 1941, to Victor&nbsp;A. Sahm, Sr. and Viva Lee (née Goodman).{{sfn|Jasinski, Laurie|2012|p=1382}} The Sahm family had migrated to the United States from Germany early in the 20th&nbsp;century, and settled initially in [[Galveston, Texas]]. Sahm's grandparents, Alfred and Alga, owned a farm near [[Cibolo, Texas]]. Alfred Sahm was a musician who played with the polka band The Sahm Boys. During the [[Great Depression]], Sahm's parents moved to San Antonio, where Victor worked at [[Kelly Field]] Air Force base.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=3}}

Sahm began singing at age five, and took up the [[steel guitar]] at age six. The same year, he appeared on San Antonio's radio station [[KSLR|KMAC]] and performed the [[Sons of the Pioneers]]' "Teardrops in My Heart".{{sfn|Helander, Brock|2001|p=632}} He was regarded as a [[child prodigy]] on the steel guitar.{{sfn|Powell, Austin|Freeman, Doug|Johnston, Daniel|2011|p=85}}{{sfn|Reid, Jan|2004|p=44}}{{sfn|Larkin, Colin|2002|p=382}} His mother took him to a local music school, but his teacher turned him down soon after. His teacher explained he could not teach Sahm to read [[musical notation|music]], and the boy could already [[playing by ear|play by ear]]. Sahm often appeared at a local club, The Barn, which his uncle co-owned with [[Charlie Walker (musician)|Charlie Walker]].{{sfn|Flippo, Chet|1971|pp=26, 27}} By the time he was eight, he could play the [[fiddle]] and [[mandolin]], and he began to appear on the ''[[Louisiana Hayride]]'' as "Little Doug".{{sfn|Jasinski, Laurie|2012|p=1382}} He also performed shows with [[Hank Williams]], [[Faron Young]] and [[Hank Thompson (musician)|Hank Thompson]]. At age thirteen, he was offered a spot on the ''[[Grand Ole Opry]]'' that his mother declined, wanting him to finish school.{{sfn|Jasinski, Laurie|2012|p=1382}} In 1953, Sahm met [[Augie Meyers]] while he purchased [[baseball card]]s at Meyer's mother's grocery store,{{sfn|Magnet staff|2002}} and the two became friends. Meyers and Sahm discussed forming a band, but nothing came of it as both played with different groups. Meyers mastered the [[accordion]], [[piano]] and [[rhythm guitar]].{{sfn|Reid, Jan| Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=10}} Sahm grew up on the East side of San Antonio, a predominantly black neighborhood. He listened from his home to the live performances of [[T-Bone Walker]] and other blues artists who appeared at a nearby blues bar, the Eastwood Country Club.{{sfn|Flippo, Chet|1971|pp=26, 27}} Sahm's neighbor, Homer Callahan, introduced him to the records of [[Howlin' Wolf]], [[Lonesome Sundown]], [[Fats Domino]], [[Jimmy Reed]], and [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] and [[Excello Records]].{{sfn|Antone's Record Label staff|1995}}

[[File:Doug-Sahm-High-School.jpg|150px|thumb|alt= Photographic portrait of Sahm in his high school years wearing sunglasses|High school portrait of Sahm, circa 1958|left]]
In 1955, producer Charlie Fitch released Sahm's debut single on Sarg Records.{{sfn|Bradley, Andy|Wood, Roger|2010|p=88}} Cataloged with the number 113-45 on the label's releases, the pairing of "A Real American Joe" with "Rollin' Rollin'" was credited to Little Doug.{{sfn|Billboard staff|1955|p=48}} The same year, Sahm formed his first band, The Kings. A year later, one of his concerts in school was interrupted by the principal after Sahm started imitating [[Elvis Presley]]'s gyrations. The students left the auditorium and headed to Sahm's house to continue listening to the band.{{sfn|Flippo, Chet|1971|pp=26, 27}} As he continued performing country music, fiddler J. R. Chatwell, who played with bandleader [[Adolph Hofner]], mentored him. The music of [[Lefty Frizzell]], Howlin' Wolf, Lonesome Sundown, Elvis Presley, [[Little Richard]], T-Bone Walker, [[Floyd Tillman]], and San Antonio musicians Johnny Owen and Ricky Aguirre influenced him during his teenage years.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=7}}{{sfn|Wolff, Kurt|2000|p=421}}{{sfn|Flippo, Chet|1971|pp=26, 27}}

Sahm enjoyed success performing in San Antonio nightclubs,{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=20}} as he played a blend of music that consisted of [[rhythm and blues]] with the addition of the West Side tenor saxophone player Eracleo "Rocky" Morales.{{sfn|Govenar, Alan|1988|p=203}} The "West Side Sound", characteristic of San Antonio, consisted of a blend of genres: [[country music]], [[conjunto]], rhythm and blues, [[polka]] and [[rock and roll]].{{sfn|Guerra, Claudia|2018|p=503}}{{sfn|Olsen, Allen|2005}}{{sfn|Patoski, Joe Nick|2020}} Meanwhile, Sahm performed on guitar six nights a week with [[Jimmy Johnson (blues guitarist)|Jimmy Johnson]]'s band.{{sfn|Flippo, Chet|1971|pp=26, 27}} Saxophonist Spot Barnett invited him to play at the Ebony rhythm and blues club.{{sfn|Magnet staff|2002}}

Sahm fronted three bands: The Pharaohs, The Dell-Kings and The Markays. He released the song "Crazy Daisy" (1959), and he had a local hit with "Why Why Why" (1960) on Renner Records.{{sfn|Gart, Gallen|2002|p=104}}{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=22}} Sahm graduated from high school the same year. He had another local hit with "Crazy, Crazy Feeling" (1961);{{sfn|Flippo, Chet|1971|pp=26, 27}} "Just A Moment" (1961) and "Lucky Me" (1963) followed.{{sfn|Larkin, Colin|2011|p=12}} By 1964, Sahm was dropped by the Renner label and he tried to convince [[Huey P. Meaux]] to sign him. Meaux, the owner of [[SugarHill Recording Studios]], was enjoying success with [[Dale Houston#Partnership with Grace Broussard|Dale and Grace]] and [[Barbara Lynn]], and turned Sahm down.{{sfn|Larkin, Colin|2002|p=382}}

==The Sir Douglas Quintet==
{{main article|Sir Douglas Quintet}}
[[File:Sir Douglas Quintet 1965.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Photograph of the five members of Sir Douglas Quintet |The Sir Douglas Quintet in 1965 (Sahm to the right)]]
Meaux produced songs that appeared on the music charts in the 1960s, but because of [[Beatlemania]] and the [[British Invasion]], his records stopped selling well. Determined to find the reason for the commercial success of [[The Beatles]] sound, Meaux said he purchased several of their records and rented three rooms at the Wayfarer Hotel in San Antonio. According to his account, he drank a case of [[Flavored fortified wine|Thunderbird wine]] in the process.{{sfn|Leigh, Spencer|2016|p=155}} Meaux felt the Beatles' songs shared a common ground with traditional [[Two-step (dance move)|two-step]] [[Cajun music]].{{sfn|Meaux, Francois|2018|p=92}} He called Sahm and asked him to write songs based on that style, and to let his hair grow.{{sfn|Leigh, Spencer|2016|p=155}} Sahm and Meyers appeared with [[The Dave Clark Five]] in San Antonio, where they were featured on the program, with their respective bands, as the opening acts. Sahm appeared with the Markays, and Meyers the Goldens.{{sfn|Busby, Mark|2004|p=340}} Meyers attributed Meaux's interest in recording Sahm and himself to their performance at the concert.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=27}}

Sahm put together a band with Meyers (keyboard), Frank Morin (saxophone), Harvey Kagan (bass) and Johnny Perez (drums).{{sfn|Larkin, Colin|2011|p=12}} Based on The Beatles' "[[She's a Woman]]", Sahm wrote a song that integrated their style with the sounds characteristic of [[tejano music]].{{sfn|Avant-Mier, Roberto|2010|p=100}} Sahm called his new composition "She's A Body Mover". Meaux purchased the song from him for $25 ({{Inflation|US|25|1964|fmt=eq|r=-2|cursign=$}}), but he felt the title would not help it get airplay. Instead, he renamed it "[[She's About a Mover]]".{{sfn|Meaux, Francois|2018|p=92}} The song was released on [[Tribe Records]] in 1965 and credited to the [[Sir Douglas Quintet]]—an "English-sounding" name created by Meaux to capitalize on the success of the British Invasion.{{sfn|Leszczak, Bob|2014|p=194}}{{sfn|Larkin, Colin|2002|p=382}} The first publicity pictures of the band were taken in silhouette to conceal the appearances of Frank Morin and Johnny Perez, the Latino members of the band.{{sfn|Avant-Mier, Roberto|2010|p=100}} "She's About a Mover" peaked at number 13 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]],{{sfn|Leszczak, Bob|2014|p=194}} and reached number 15 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].{{sfn|Rees, Dafydd|Crampton, Luke|1991|p=26}} The success of the song propelled the Sir Douglas Quintet to tour, and to become an opener for The Beatles and [[The Beach Boys]].{{sfn|Buckley, Peter|2003|p=942}} They appeared on ''[[Hullabaloo (TV series)|Hullabaloo]]'', and host [[Trini Lopez]] revealed the real origin of the band. The quintet toured the United States with [[James Brown]], and Europe with The Beach Boys and the [[Rolling Stones]].{{sfn|Curtis, Gregory|1974|p=47}}

{{Listen |type=music |filename=Sir Douglas Quintet - She's About a Mover.ogg|title="She's About a Mover" |description=Sahm Performing with the Sir Douglas Quintet}}
After meeting Sahm in [[New York City]] in 1965, [[Bob Dylan]] said in an interview he felt the Sir Douglas Quintet would be a commercial success on radio. Dylan and Sahm met again in [[London]] while the Sir Douglas Quintet toured England.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=34, 35}} During a stop in [[Corpus Christi, Texas]], in December 1965, Sahm and Morin were arrested for possession of [[marijuana]]{{sfn|Walraven, Bill|1965|p=1}} upon their arrival at the [[Corpus Christi International Airport]]. The bond for the musicians' release was set at $1,500 ({{Inflation|US|1500|1965|fmt=eq|r=-2|cursign=$}}). Sahm got the money from his family in San Antonio.{{sfn|Walraven, Bill|1965|p=[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/67955704/arrest-part-2/ 12]}} The band pleaded guilty to the charge of "receiving and concealing marijuana without paying the required transfer tax". Judge [[Reynaldo Guerra Garza]] sentenced them to probation with supervision for five years in March 1966.{{sfn|Corpus Christi Caller-Times staff|1966|p=B1}} Meyers was forbidden from leaving Texas for the duration of his probation.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=37}} A series of appearances with the band in small towns around the state made Sahm unhappy. After his parole officer allowed him to leave Texas the same year, he decided to move to [[California]] with his wife and children.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=38}}

==Move to California and return to Texas ==
Sahm moved to [[Salinas, California]], and became involved in [[San Francisco]]'s burgeoning [[hippie]] scene.{{sfn|Magnet staff|2002}} He gathered again with the musicians of the Sir Douglas Quintet, excluding Meyers, whose parole officer did not allow to leave Texas.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=41}} Sahm became acquainted with the music acts playing in the [[Haight-Ashbury]] district, and performed at venues including [[The Fillmore]] and the [[Avalon Ballroom]].{{sfn|Magnet staff|2002}} Through audio engineer [[Dan Healy (soundman)|Dan Healy]], Sahm met and befriended [[Jerry Garcia]]. The Sir Douglas Quintet opened for the [[Grateful Dead]] in [[Oakland, California]],{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=43}} and in October 1966 performed with [[Big Brother and the Holding Company]] featuring [[Janis Joplin]].{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=44}} Helped by lawyer Brian Rohan, who represented the Grateful Dead, Sahm was signed to [[Mercury Records]] and its subsidiary labels.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=44}} In December 1968, Sahm appeared with his son, Shawn, on the cover of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine. His arrival in San Francisco with the other Texan musicians was covered in the feature "Tribute to the Lone Star State: Dispossessed Men and Mothers of Texas".{{sfn|Sepulvado, Larry|Burks, John|1968}} During the photo shooting, Sahm took his son and sat him on his lap to emulate a childhood photograph that had been taken of him with Hank Williams.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=12}} In 1969, Meyers joined Sahm in San Francisco for the recording of ''[[Mendocino (album)|Mendocino]]''.{{sfn|Magnet staff|2002}} The album's title track reached number 27 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100''.{{sfn|Whitburn, Joel|1990|p=226}}

[[File:Doug Sahm - Atlantic Records Publicity Portrait 1973(derivate).jpg|thumb|200px|right|alt= Photograph of Sahm holding a fiddle and bow talking to a man in a recording studio |Sahm recording for Atlantic Records in 1972]]
Sahm left California in 1971 and returned to San Antonio.{{sfn|Jasinski, Laurie|2012|p=1383}} He released an album entitled ''The Return of Doug Saldaña'' with the Sir Douglas Quintet; [[Chicano]] musicians in San Antonio had given him the nickname "Saldaña".{{sfn|Avant-Mier, Roberto|2010|p=100}} A cover of "[[Wasted Days and Wasted Nights]]" on the album helped to reignite the career of its original singer, [[Freddy Fender]].{{sfn|Riemenschneider, Chris 2|1999|p=32}} The same year, ''Rolling Stone'' featured Sahm on its cover again and ran his interview with [[Chet Flippo]].{{sfn|Flippo, Chet|1971|pp=26, 27}}

Sahm moved to Austin that year as the local hippie scene grew. He appeared at the [[Armadillo World Headquarters]] and the Soap Creek Saloon in Austin.{{sfn|Magnet staff|2002}} In 1972, he disbanded the Sir Douglas Quintet.{{sfn|Jasinski, Laurie|2012|p=1383}} The same year, he made a cameo appearance in the film ''[[Cisco Pike]]'', starring [[Kris Kristofferson]].{{sfn|Kubernik, Harvey|2006|p=89}} Sahm performed on the film's song "Michoacan", but radio stations refused to play it because of its references to marijuana.{{sfn|Riemenschneider, Chris 2|1999|p=32}}

{{Listen |type=music |filename=Doug Sahm - Groover's Paradise.ogg|title="Groover's Paradise" |description=Sahm performing the title-tack of his album}}
[[Jerry Wexler]] signed Sahm to the newly created [[progressive country]] division of Atlantic Records in 1972. In October 1972, he recorded ''[[Doug Sahm and Band]]'' in New York City with guest appearances by Bob Dylan, [[Dr. John]], [[David "Fathead" Newman]], [[Flaco Jimenez]], [[David Bromberg]] and [[Kenny Kosek]].{{sfn|Billboard staff|p=18|1973}} The release garnered mixed reviews and sold poorly,{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|p=107|2010}} reaching number 125 on [[Billboard 200|''Billboard''{{'}}s Top LPs & Tapes]].{{sfn|Lazell, Barry|1989|p=462}} In February 1973, he joined [[Willie Nelson]] during the recording of ''[[Shotgun Willie]]'' in New York City and featured on the album with his own musicians.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|2004|p=224}} Sahm also joined the Grateful Dead's recording sessions.{{sfn|Sansone, Glen|1999|p=5}} As he continued to enjoy success in Austin's venues, Sahm used material left over from his October 1972 sessions with Atlantic Records for his 1973 release ''Texas Tornado''.{{sfn|Magnet staff|2002}} Atlantic folded its country music division in 1973.{{sfn|Country Music Magazine staff|1994|p=53}} The following year [[Warner Records]] released his next album,{{sfn|DiMartino, Dave|1994|p=217}} ''[[Groover's Paradise]]'', featuring [[Doug Clifford]] and [[Stu Cook]], former musicians in [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]].{{sfn|Magnet staff|2002}} ''[[Texas Monthly]]'' wrote the album captured Austin's "insouciant essence" as a "carefree hippie mecca".{{sfn|Denberg, Jody|1984|p=228}} As he toured to promote the album, Sahm made his debut performance at [[Carnegie Hall]].{{sfn|Schulian, John|1974|p=C1}}

Sahm's record sales continued to decline,{{sfn|Magnet staff|2002}} and he rarely performed concerts outside the Austin club scene.{{sfn|Patoski, Joe Nick|1977|p=118}} In 1975, he produced former [[The 13th Floor Elevators|13th Floor Elevators]] front man [[Roky Erickson]] following Erickson's release from Rusk State Hospital.{{sfn|Stegall, Tim|2019}} In 1976, Sahm collaborated again with Meaux on the release of ''[[Texas Rock For Country Rollers]]''. Besides vocals, Sahm played lead guitar, fiddle and piano. Meyers also joined the project and performed on the piano and organ.{{sfn|Bradley, Andy|Wood, Roger|2010|p=201}} The same year, Sahm appeared on the fifth episode of the first season of ''[[Austin City Limits]]''.{{sfn|Laird, Tracey|2014|p=40}} In 1979, he made a cameo appearance in the film ''[[More American Graffiti]]''.{{sfn|Gray, Michael|2006|p=596}}

==The 1980s, the Texas Tornados and the 1990s==
Sahm released two albums on [[Takoma Records]]: the solo record ''[[Hell of a Spell]]'' (1980), followed by a collaboration with the Sir Douglas Quintet on ''[[Border Wave]]'' (1981).{{sfn|Helander, Brock|2001|p=632}} Sahm reformed the band after it had gained momentum from the success of [[new wave music]], and the use of organs featured by [[Elvis Costello]] and [[The Attractions]].{{sfn|Riemenschneider, Chris 2|1999|p=32}} Sahm and the Sir Douglas Quintet then signed a record deal with the Swedish label [[Sonet Records]] in 1983.{{sfn|Magnet staff|2002}} Their release ''Midnight Sun'', became a success: It sold 50,000 copies in Sweden, another 50,000 copies in the rest of [[Scandinavia]],{{sfn|Denberg, Jody|1984|p=228}} and reached number 27 on the [[Sverigetopplistan|Topplistan]].{{sfn|Sverigetopplistan staff|2020}} Its single "Meet Me in Stockholm" became a hit.{{sfn|Gale Research staff|1989|p=260}} ''Midnight Sun'', and their second release with the label, ''Rio Medina'', were recorded in the United States. Sahm and the Sir Douglas Quintet toured Scandinavia and also played in the [[Netherlands]].{{sfn|Denberg, Jody|1984|p=228}} By 1985, Sahm had moved to [[Canada]] after he visited friends in [[Vancouver]], but he returned to Austin every year to take part in the [[South by Southwest]] festival.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|pp=161–163}} He formed the band The Texas Mavericks in Austin in 1987 with Alvin Crow (fiddle), Speedy Sparks (bass), John Reed (guitar), and Ernie Durawa (drums).{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=156}} Sahm sang under the pseudonym "Samm Dogg", and he and the band performed wearing [[wrestling mask]]s.{{sfn|Swenson, John|1987}} Meanwhile, in Canada, along with [[Amos Garrett]] and [[Gene Taylor (pianist)|Gene Taylor]], he recorded ''[[The Return of the Formerly Brothers]]''. The release earned them the [[Juno Awards|Juno Award]] for [[Juno Award for Best Roots and Traditional Album|Best Roots and Traditional Album]] in 1989.{{sfn|Mackie, John|1989|p=B6}} In September 1989, six years after  his last record release in the United States, Sahm partnered with club owner and blues impresario [[Clifford Antone]] for the release of ''[[Juke Box Music (Doug Sahm album)|Juke Box Music]]'' on [[Antone's Record Label]].{{sfn|Denberg, Jody|1989|p=128}} By the end of the decade, Sahm often performed at the Austin night club Antone's.{{sfn|McLeese, Don|1995|p=B6}} He used the club's house band on the recording.{{sfn|Denberg, Jody|1989|p=130}}

{{Listen |type=music |filename=Texas Tornados - Soy de San Luis.ogg|title="Soy de San Luis" |description=Sahm singing with the Texas Tornados}}
In 1989, Sahm formed the [[Texas Tornados]] with Meyers (organ, vocals), Fender (guitar, vocals) and Jimenez (accordion, vocals). The group's songs featured the Tex-Mex sound—a mixture of rock, country music, conjunto and blues.{{sfn|Marks, Craig|1993|p=18}}{{sfn|Hartman, Gary|2008|p=208}} Warner Brothers signed the band to a recording contract, and in 1991 they released ''[[Texas Tornados (album)|Texas Tornados]]''.{{sfn|Jasinski, Laurie|2012|p=1538}} The album charted at number five on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard's]]'' [[Top Country Albums]]. Meanwhile, it earned the [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Mexican/Mexican-American Album|Best Mexican/Mexican-American Album]]. A version of the album sung in Spanish entitled ''Los Texas Tornados'' was released at the same time.{{sfn|Jasinski, Laurie|2012|p=1539}} The band appeared in Europe and Japan.{{sfn|Ellingham, Mark|1999|p=505}} Along with Willie Nelson, the Texas Tornados were featured at the [[first inauguration of Bill Clinton]].{{sfn|Riemenschneider, Chris 2|1999|p=32}} The band performed at the America's Reunion on [[National Mall|the Mall]] event, as well as in other venues around Washington, D.C. during their stay.{{sfn|Austin-American Statesman staff|1993|p=A13}}

In 1994, Sahm and Meyers formed a new version of the Sir Douglas Quintet. It included Sahm's sons Shawn on guitar and [[Shandon Sahm|Shandon]] on drums.{{sfn|Huey, Steve|2021}} The band released the album ''Day Dreaming at Midnight''.{{sfn|Chadbourne, Eugene|2021}} Sahm then formed The Last Real Texas Blues Band with the musicians he performed with at Antone's. In 1995, the group, composed of Rocky Morales (tenor saxophone), Sauce Gonzalez (Hammond organ), Meyers (piano), [[Denny Freeman]] (guitar) and Derek O'Brian (guitar), recorded a studio album of their live performances. Antone's Record Label released it as ''[[The Last Real Texas Blues Band Featuring Doug Sahm]]''. The album included standards by T-Bone Walker and [[Lowell Fulson]].{{sfn|McLeese, Don|1995|p=B6}} It was nominated for the [[Grammy Awards|Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Blues Album|Best Traditional Blues Album]].{{sfn|Grammy staff|2021}}

Sahm and the Texas Tornados' song "A Little Bit is Better Than Nada" was featured in the 1996 film ''[[Tin Cup]]''.{{sfn|Riemenschneider, Chris 2|1999|p=32}} In 1998, Sahm collaborated with [[The Gourds]] for the release ''[[Get a Life (Doug Sahm album)|S.D.Q. 98']]''.{{sfn|Magnet staff|2002}} The same year, he joined the Latino supergroup [[Los Super Seven]].{{sfn|Harrington, Richard|1999}} By 1999, impressed by Dallas singer Ed Burleson, Sahm assembled a band that consisted of [[Bill Kirchen]] (guitar), Tommy Detamore and Clay Baker (steel guitars) and Alvin Crow (fiddle). Sahm booked the Cherry Ridge Studios in [[Floresville, Texas]], and he assisted with the recording of Burleson's debut album ''My Perfect World''. The album was the first release on Sahm's own label, Tornado Records. Using the same band, Sahm extended the booking at Cherry Ridge Studios for a series of recording sessions during July and August 1999.{{sfn|Renshaw, Jerry|2000}}

==Personal life==
Sahm met Violet Morris at a Christmas party in 1961. At the time, Morris worked as an executive secretary at a [[Montgomery Ward]] department store. The couple married in 1963. Morris had three children from a previous marriage, and in 1964, she gave birth to Dawn Sahm.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=23}} As he was responsible for his wife and four children, Sahm was classified 1-Y on the [[Selective Service System#1948–1976|Selective Service System]].{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=24}} His first son, Shawn, was born in 1965,{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=36}} and Shandon in 1969.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=47}}

In 1973, during a visit to the Mexican restaurant La Rosa in San Antonio, Sahm was apprehended by police officers who searched him, his car, and his companions for drugs. As they searched the car, his fiddle was broken.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=107-108}} After being handcuffed, Sahm was beaten by the police officers as he continued to protest and move. He was arrested for public intoxication.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=109}} The case was dismissed at his trial in June 1973, and Sahm unsuccessfully tried to sue the city.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=110}} Violet had already been unhappy with the marriage because of Sahm's numerous affairs,{{sfn|Davis, John|2010|p=G6}} and after his arrest, they divorced.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=111}}

Sahm was a dedicated follower of [[baseball]]. He followed several teams and visited their training camps through the years. He often refused to attend rehearsals to watch games, and on one occasion, he rejected a tour to be able to watch the [[World Series]].{{sfn|Magnet staff|2002}}{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=Prologue}}

==Death==

By the end of 1999, Sahm decided to take a vacation trip to [[New Mexico]]. He planned to visit a friend in [[Taos, New Mexico]], then continue to a cabin in the [[Sangre de Cristo Range]] and finish the trip with a visit to Dan Healy in San Francisco.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=177}} Sahm left for New Mexico after a brief visit with his son Shawn in [[Boerne, Texas]]. During the trip, Sahm called his son to inform him he had been feeling ill and that he often had to pull over to vomit. Sahm checked into the Kachina Lodge Hotel in [[Taos, New Mexico]]. His son continued calling him over the next few days. Sahm's girlfriend, Debora Hanson, and Shawn offered to fly to New Mexico and drive him back to Texas. Sahm initially refused, but he agreed to drive himself to [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]], to meet Hanson there for the drive back to Texas.{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=179}} As his condition worsened, he asked a clerk about local doctors who would do house calls. Sahm was advised to visit the local emergency room, but he did not do so.{{sfn|Lerner, David|2019|p=8-9}} On November 18, 1999, Sahm was found dead in his hotel room. Local authorities determined it to be a death by [[Manner of death|natural causes]], but an autopsy was ordered.{{sfn|Cromelin, Richard|1999}}{{sfn|Chicago Tribune staff|1999}} The results of the autopsy determined that Sahm died of [[Arteriosclerotic heart disease|arteriosclerotic cardiovascular disease]], described as a heart attack.{{sfn|Burr, Ramiro|1999|p=6}} The [[Music & Entertainment Television|Austin Music Network]] aired a three-hour tribute to Sahm, while [[KUT]] dedicated an episode of one of its shows to his music. A memorial concert was announced to take place at Antone's in December 1999.{{sfn|Riemenschneider, Chris|1999|p=B4}}

On November 23, 1999, Sahm's funeral took place at the Sunset Memorial Home in San Antonio.{{sfn|Riemenschneider, Chris|1999|p=B4}} Loudspeakers were placed outside of the funeral home for the service to be heard by the estimated one thousand mourners in attendance. According to the ''[[Austin American Statesman]]'', the crowd consisted of people "across all lines of age, race, and social standing".{{sfn|Corcoran, Michael|1999|p=1}} The viewing lasted an hour and a half, as the mourners passed Sahm's casket and left keepsakes. Freddy Fender chose not to attend the funeral to avoid distracting the crowds with his presence.{{sfn|Corcoran, Michael|1999|p=1}} Bob Dylan, [[Bruce Springsteen]],{{sfn|Riemenschneider, Chris|1999|p=B4}} then-Texas governor [[George W. Bush]], and Willie Nelson reached out to the family to express their condolences.{{sfn|Corcoran, Michael|1999|p=A1}} A planned tribute by a local radio station had to be called off, as the viewing took longer than expected, and the station's programming moved to the broadcast of the weather report.{{sfn|Corcoran, Michael 2|1999|p=A17}} Sahm was buried in a private ceremony at Sunset Memorial Park in San Antonio, next to his mother and father.{{sfn|Corcoran, Michael 2|1999|p=A17}}{{sfn|Jasinski, Laurie|2012|p=1382}}

In July 2000, the songs recorded at the Cherry Ridge Studios sessions the previous year were released on the posthumous album ''[[The Return of Wayne Douglas]]''.{{sfn|Renshaw, Jerry|2000}}

==Legacy==
His long hair and sideburns, his use of sunglasses and his preference for western attire including cowboy hats and boots characterized Sahm's look.{{sfn|Powell, Austin|Freeman, Doug|Johnston, Daniel|2011|p=131}}{{sfn|McLeese, Don|1995|p=B6}}{{sfn|Busby, Mark|2004|p=340}}{{sfn|Flippo, Chet|1971|pp=26, 27}} His music style encompassed country music, blues, rock and roll, Cajun music, rhythm and blues, [[doo-wop]] and tejano music. [[Psychedelic music]] during his time in San Francisco, [[jazz music|jazz]] and the compositions of Bob Dylan later influenced him.{{sfn|Magnet staff|2002}}{{sfn|Curtis, Gregory|1974|p=46}}{{sfn|Walker, Jesse|2004|p=144}}{{sfn|Corcoran, Michael 3|1999|p=30}} Sahm's presence was described as "impulsive, restless and energetic" by ''[[Texas Monthly]]'',{{sfn|Denberg, Jody|1989|p=130}} while his way of talking was characterized by a "rapid-fire" style and the use of hippie [[jargon]].{{sfn|Denberg, Jody|1989|p=130}}{{sfn|Hilburn, Robert|1974|p=58}} A [[multi-instrumentalist]], Sahm mastered the steel guitar, mandolin, fiddle, electric guitar, electric bass, [[dobro]], [[bajo sexto]], drums and piano.{{sfn|Burr, Ramiro|1999|p=6}}{{sfn|Reid, Jan|Sahm, Shawn|2010|p=16}}{{sfn|Joynson, Vernon|1984|p=93}}{{sfn|Patoski, Joe Nick|2000}}

[[File:Doug Sahm Hill sign.jpg|thumb|200px|alt=Sign marking Doug Sahm Hill with the Independent building seen in the background|Sign marking "Doug Sahm Hill" with [[The Independent (Austin, Texas)|The Independent]] building seen in the background]]
''Rolling Stone'' wrote that "Lone Star music, at its best, in every form, was religion to Sahm."{{sfn|Fricke, David|2009}} The magazine ranked him at number 60 on their 100 Greatest Country Artists of All Time in 2017.{{sfn|Rolling Stone staff|2017}} To ''Billboard'', Sahm was a "central figure in the world of Tex-Mex".{{sfn|Burr, Ramiro|1999|p=6}} ''[[New Musical Express]]'' considered him "an unpaid PR man for the state of Texas and all things Texan".{{sfn|NME staff|1999}} The ''[[New York Times]]'' saw Sahm as "a patriarch of Texas rock and country music".{{sfn|Pareles, Jon|1999|p=28A}} ''[[Lone Star Music|Lone Star Music Magazine]]'' called him "the Godfather of San Antonio rock 'n' roll".{{sfn|Hisaw, Eric|2010}} The ''[[Austin Chronicle]]'' commented: "If Texas had such designation, Douglas Wayne Sahm would be the State Musician of Texas."{{sfn|Moser, Margaret|1999}} ''[[AllMusic]]'' deemed the singer "a highly knowledgeable and superbly competent performer of Texan musical styles".{{sfn|TiVo Staff|2010}}

Sahm was featured in the 1974 mural "Austintatious" at the [[Drag (Austin, Texas)|Drag portion]] of Guadalupe street in Austin.{{sfn|Price, Asher|2014}} He was inducted into the Austin Music Awards Hall of Fame with the 1982–1983 class.{{sfn|Austin Chronicle staff|2021}} In 2002, the [[Americana Music Association]] gave him the [[Americana Music Honors & Awards|President's Award]].{{sfn|Waddel, Ray|2002|p=27}} On October 13, 2002, San Antonio's mayor [[Edward D. Garza|Ed Garza]] declared the date "Doug Sahm Day" in the city.{{sfn|Blackstock, Peter|2002}} In 2008, Sahm was an inaugural inductee to the Austin Music Memorial.{{sfn|Head, James|Jasinski, Laurie|2021}} On April 10, 2008, [[Austin City Council]] approved the motion to rename the spiral hill in  Butler Metro Park to Doug Sahm Hill, in recognition of his "great talents in the music industry".{{sfn|Austin City Council|2008}} The {{convert|35|ft|abbr=off|adj=on}} hill is the highest point in the park, with a 360° view of Austin's skyline.{{sfn|Llewellin, Charlie|2019|p=99}} In November 2009, artist David Blancas completed ''La Música de San Anto'' for the [[San Anto Cultural Arts]] Community Mural Program. Located on the west side of San Antonio, the {{convert|141 x 17|ft|abbr=off|adj=on|round=each}} mural features San Antonio musicians including Sahm.{{sfn|San Anto staff|2009}} Blancas restored the mural in 2020.{{sfn|Martin, Deborah|2020}} [[Federico Archuleta]] also painted two murals in Austin depicting Sahm.{{sfn|Faires, Robert|2010|p=26, 28}}

In 2009, a tribute album recorded by San Antonio musicians, ''Keep Your Soul: A Tribute to Doug Sahm'', was released.{{sfn|Fricke, David|2009}} On Sahm's birthday, November 6, 2010, a plaque was added to the top of Doug Sahm Hill. The plaque features a caricature of Sahm by [[Kerry Awn]] and a short biography written by ''Austin Chronicle's'' music columnist [[Margaret Moser]].{{sfn|Dunlop, Machelle|2011}} Also in 2010, Shawn Sahm and the Texas Tornados released the album ''¡Está bueno!''. Sahm's son and the surviving members of the group toured promoting the album.{{sfn|Lopetegui, Enrique|2011}} In 2015, Sahm was inducted to the South Texas Music Walk of Fame.{{sfn|Head, James|Jasinski, Laurie|2021}} The same year, music writer Joe Nick Patoski premiered his documentary on Sahm ''Sir Doug and the Genuine Texas Cosmic Groove'' at the South by Southwest festival.{{sfn|Patoski, Joe Nick|2015}} Patoski started a petition to induct Sahm into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]].{{sfn|Whittaker, Richard|2015}} The film was re-released in 2022, and a special screening in San Antonio featured a Q&A section that included original Sir Douglas Quintet members Meyers and Jack Barber.{{sfn|Frías, Hannah|2022}} Music producer Kevin Kosub established a small museum featuring memorabilia from Sahm's career.{{sfn|Buffkin, Travis|2016}}

On [[Record Store Day]] 2023, a 1971 [[soundboard recording]] of Sahm during a live performance at the [[Troubadour (West Hollywood, California)|Troubador]] in Los Angeles was released on vinyl LP under the name ''Texas Tornado Live: Doug Weston's Troubadour, 1971''.{{sfn|Ruggiero, Bob|2023}} The Same year, [[Son Volt]] released ''Day of the Doug'', a tribute album to Doug Sahm. It features 12 songs that span Sahm’s career as a solo artist as well as his work with Sir Douglas Quintet and the Texas Tornados. The Intro and Outro tracks consisted of phone messages that Sahm left [[Jay Farrar]] over the years.{{sfn|Glide staff|2023}}

